{"id": 225038556, "title": "How Your Closest Business Friends Can Catapult Your Success", "text": "Share to Facebook Share to Twitter Share to Linkedin B.D. Dalton II the Lazy Overachiever, writer and dealmaker brings 25 years of success and failure. Director at Rockfine Group. getty Jim Rohn is often credited with saying, \u201cYou are the average of the five people you spend the most time with.\u201d Imagine sitting in a room where the energy is buzzing with innovation, the walls echo with the laughter of camaraderie, and every face around you is lit up with the excitement of shared discovery. This is not just any meeting but a gathering of minds\u2014my five closest business friends, or what I like to call my \"next-level group.\" Together, we've turned routine group meetings into a powerhouse of strategic execution and mutual growth. This was my number one tool to build my business in the U.K. following two successes in the U.S. In the fast-paced world of business, it\u2019s easy to get lost in the whirlwind of day-to-day operations and short-term goals. However, I've found the true essence of sustainable success lies in stepping back and leveraging collective wisdom. If you need someone to just focus on your business, then you can hire a non-exec director for typically between \u00a31,000 and \u00a310,000-plus a month, depending on your needs and specific needs, or use this awesome alternative. Leveling Up Here\u2019s a story about how our group transformed not just my professional trajectory but also our individual perspectives, acting as a pseudo-non-executive director board for each other. Three years ago, during one of our monthly meetups, while discussing market strategies over coffee, a simple suggestion from a group member led me to pivot my entire marketing approach. The result? Triple-digit growth in user engagement and a significant reduction in churn. It was a game-changing moment, made possible by a friend who understood my business almost as well as I did yet could offer fresh, unbiased perspectives. MORE FOR YOU Trump Trial Prosecutor Ends Closing Argument After Nearly 5 Hours\u2014Jury Instructions Set For Wednesday Gas Explosion In Downtown Youngstown Ohio Injures At Least 7 Trump Lashes Out At Robert De Niro After Actor Calls Him A Tyrant Outside Courthouse Expanding on this transformative experience, let me highlight how learning from different industries has sparked innovation within our group. For instance, a member from the healthcare sector shared insights on compliance and patient engagement technologies. Adapting these principles, I developed a customer loyalty system that mirrored patient engagement strategies, significantly enhancing long-term customer relationships in my tech business. Another group member, a seasoned real estate developer, introduced us to the concept of location analytics and its potential beyond real estate. By integrating these analytics into retail strategies, I was able to optimize store locations and inventory distribution, which led to a significant increase in sales in underperforming regions. To-Do List To Forge Your Next Level Group Now, let me guide you through creating your own next-level group, a circle of professionals who can significantly amplify your ability to navigate from \"cloud to ground\"\u2014shifting seamlessly from strategy to tactics. 1. Identify diverse experts. Select professionals from different industries or specializations. The diversity brings unique perspectives and insights that can challenge conventional thinking and spur creativity. 2. Set structured meeting times. Commit to regular meetings, whether monthly or quarterly. Regularity builds rhythm and ensures that the group remains a priority for everyone involved. 3. Establish ground rules. To foster openness and trust, set clear expectations about confidentiality, punctuality and the nature of the feedback provided. This framework encourages productive and respectful exchanges. 4. Focus on actionable insights. Ensure that each session has a clear agenda and that everyone leaves with actionable advice or strategies that they can implement immediately. This practice maximizes the value of each meeting. 5. Commit to mutual growth. The group should not only focus on business but also on personal development. Encouraging each other to pursue broader goals can lead to unexpected opportunities and deeper professional relationships. The power of such a group is not just in the regularity of meetings but in the depth of the relationships and the commitment to pushing each other forward. By integrating one-on-one coaching with these group interactions, each member can address personal challenges while benefiting from group momentum. Through engaging in peer-to-peer groups, I\u2019ve seen professionals evolve from making decisions in isolation to being well-rounded leaders who adeptly move from grand vision strategies to effective tactical actions. This model doesn't just add a layer of accountability; it multiplies the networks, resources and capabilities of every member. In the spirit of our group's founding principle, remember that \u201cIf you want to go fast, go alone; if you want to go far, go together.\u201d Start building your group today, and see just how far you can go when you take it to the next level. Forbes Business Council is the foremost growth and networking organization for business owners and leaders. Do I qualify? Follow me on LinkedIn. Check out my website. B.D. Dalton Editorial Standards Print Reprints & Permissions", "summary": "The true essence of sustainable success lies in stepping back and leveraging collective wisdom.", "url": "https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbesbusinesscouncil/2024/05/29/how-your-closest-business-friends-can-catapult-your-success/", "image": "https://imageio.forbes.com/specials-images/imageserve/6655f3fae25350bb284d38c9/0x0.jpg?format=jpg&height=900&width=1600&fit=bounds", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-05-29 13:45:00", "author": "B.D. Dalton,Forbes Councils Member", "authors": ["B.D. Dalton", "Forbes Councils Member"], "language": "en", "source_country": "US", "sentiment": 0.242}